            <notesStmt>
                <note type="summary">
                    
                        <p>Letter from Robert Monteith (1879-1956), a founder member of the Irish Volunteers, to his wife Mary Florence (Mollie)  Monteith (née McEvoy, 1877-1960). In 1909 Monteith, a Protestant, and McEvoy, a Catholic widow with three children, were married against his family&#39;s wishes. </p>
                    
                        <p></p>
                    
                        <p>In 1915 Monteith was selected by Thomas Clarke (1858–1916), a veteran of revolutionary politics, to accompany Sir Roger Casement (1864–1916), to Germany to assist with recruitment  of an Irish Brigade from the Irish prisoners-of-war. </p>
                    
                        <p></p>
                    
                        <p>In this letter, written on Christmas day, Robert expresses loneliness and states that he misses his family. He recalls times they spent together and pleads with his wife to write to him.</p>
                    
                </note>
